{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"A file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed, not only files placed directly in the root directory.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"`\"file placed inside a subdirectory of the watched root is processed\"` requires proving a real filesystem-watch path plus externally visible processing result (round-trip side effect), which unit-only tests cannot validate. MOCK-HIDE applies because mocked watcher events can miss real recursive-watch behavior.","test_description":"Run the daemon against a real temp input/output directory tree. Create `input/subdir/a.txt` after startup, then assert exactly one transformed output artifact appears in the real output directory for that file within timeout.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.78,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"The deduplication logic correctly discards a second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"Evidence quote gate: `\"second processing request for the same file path within a configurable time window\"` indicates cross-component handoff/state propagation (request ingress -> dedup gate -> pipeline enqueue), beyond a single pure function. Rejected System because behavior text does not require real OS/network/subprocess contracts; rejected Agentic/Workflow because no AI/ML dependency.","test_description":"Wire watcher-event ingestion (or request intake) + dedup module + queue in-process with a controllable clock. Submit two requests for identical path within the configured window and assert only one enqueue/process call occurs; submit again after window expiry and assert processing resumes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.34,"Integration":0.58,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When the operating system emits multiple filesystem events for a single file write, the daemon processes the file exactly once.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly depends on real OS event semantics: `\"operating system emits multiple filesystem events\"`. This is REAL-INFRA and cannot be trusted with in-process fakes; success also requires externally visible exactly-once processing outcome.","test_description":"On a real filesystem watcher, perform a write pattern known to emit multiple events (create + append/rename) for one file, then verify only one output artifact/job completion is produced for that source path.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.92,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"If the watched directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running, the daemon resumes watching the new directory without a restart.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"`\"directory is removed and then recreated while the daemon is running\"` is OS-level watcher lifecycle behavior. Unit/integration fakes can miss re-subscription failures. SYSTEM TRIAD #3 applies because resumed watching must be proven via real post-recreate file processing readback.","test_description":"Start daemon on a real watched directory, delete that directory, recreate it at same path, then add a new file and assert it is processed without restarting the daemon process.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.06,"System":0.91,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"Evidence quote gate: `\"multiple files arrive at the same time\"` + `\"processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps\"` targets ordering across intake, metadata extraction, and queue scheduling modules. Rejected System because behavior text does not explicitly require validating OS-specific timestamp contract/error shape; ordering policy can be verified with controlled fixture metadata in-process. Rejected Agentic/Workflow: no model decision path.","test_description":"Use integrated pipeline components with deterministic test fixtures for file metadata timestamps. Inject concurrent arrivals, assert processing sequence matches ascending creation timestamp and remains stable for ties per defined policy.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.22,"Integration":0.62,"System":0.14,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"This is a real filesystem timing/visibility condition: `\"still being written to when the arrival event fires\"`. Mocked dependencies can hide partial-write races. Requires round-trip proof that processing starts only after completion on real IO.","test_description":"With daemon running on a real directory, open a file and write it in chunks with delays while keeping write handle active; assert no processing output appears mid-write, then close/flushed write and assert processing occurs afterward.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.09,"System":0.88,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
